AP Environmental Science — Unit 1: The Living World: Ecosystems

Q1. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S17Q1)
Which of the following best explains how competition for resources influences species interactions within an ecosystem?
  • A. Competition primarily leads to increased biodiversity as species evolve new ways to utilize resources.
  • B. Competition for limited resources can lead to niche partitioning, resource partitioning, or competitive exclusion among species.
  • C. Competition encourages cooperation between species to share limited resources more efficiently.
  • D. Competition only occurs between individuals of the same species and does not influence interspecies interactions.

  • B. Tropical savanna
  • C. Boreal forest (Taiga)
  • D. Tundra

  • A. The conversion of atmospheric nitrogen gas into ammonia.
  • B. The conversion of nitrates back into atmospheric nitrogen gas.
  • C. The breakdown of organic nitrogen compounds into ammonia.
  • D. The conversion of ammonia/ammonium into nitrites, and then into nitrates.

  • A. The phosphorus cycle includes a large atmospheric reservoir.
  • B. The phosphorus cycle lacks a significant gaseous phase and primarily cycles through rock and water.
  • C. The phosphorus cycle is driven primarily by biological processes, not geological.
  • D. The phosphorus cycle is a much faster cycle than the carbon or nitrogen cycles.

  • D. Precipitation
Q8. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S17Q8)
Which of the following best describes the initial acquisition of solar energy in most ecosystems?
  • A. Producers (autotrophs) convert solar energy into chemical energy through photosynthesis.
  • B. Primary consumers directly absorb solar energy through their skin.
  • C. Decomposers break down dead organic matter to release stored solar energy.
  • D. Consumers indirectly acquire solar energy by metabolizing water.
Q9. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S17Q9)
Which statement accurately describes the flow of energy and the cycling of matter in an ecosystem?
  • A. Energy is recycled efficiently within an ecosystem, while matter flows in one direction.
  • B. Both energy and matter are recycled efficiently within an ecosystem.
  • C. Matter flows in one direction through an ecosystem, while energy is recycled.
  • D. Energy flows in one direction through an ecosystem and is largely lost as heat, while matter cycles.
Q10. (ID: ap_environmental_science_MCQ_U1S17Q10)
If a primary producer level in an ecosystem contains $10,000$ kcal of energy, and the trophic levels follow the $10\%$ rule for energy transfer, how much energy would be available to the secondary consumers?
  • A. $1,000$ kcal
  • B. $100,000$ kcal
  • C. $100$ kcal
  • D. $10$ kcal

  • A. Two different species of birds fighting over the same nesting site.
  • B. Two male deer of the same species fighting for a mate.
  • C. A population of rabbits growing rapidly due to abundant food.
  • D. A predator eating its prey.

  • A. High annual precipitation and deciduous trees.
  • B. Warm temperatures year-round and dense, broadleaf vegetation.
  • C. Low annual precipitation and sparse, drought-adapted vegetation.
  • D. Long, cold winters and coniferous forests.

  • B. The bottom layer of a lake where decomposition occurs.
  • C. The area near the shore where sunlight reaches the bottom.
  • D. The upper layer of water where sufficient sunlight penetrates for photosynthesis.

  • D. It cycles slowly, often trapped in sediments or rock, and has no significant atmospheric phase.

  • B. $100$ kcal
  • C. $1,000$ kcal
  • D. $10,000$ kcal
